Q FEVER - ARGENTINA: (CORDOBA) TICKS, FIRST REPORT
**************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Feb 2013
Source: Emerg Infect Dis Volume 19, Number 2 [edited]
http://dx.doi.org/10.3201/eid1902.120362


Coxiella burnetii in ticks, Argentina
------------------------------

The Gammaproteobacterium _Coxiella burnetii_ is the causative agent of acute Q fever and chronic endocarditis in humans worldwide. It is transmitted primarily by aerosol route or by ingestion of fomites from infected animals, mostly from domestic ruminants. Although over 40 tick species can be infected with _C. burnetii_, direct transmission of this agent to humans from infected ticks has never been properly documented. However, ticks may play a critical role in the transmission of _C. burnetii_ among wild vertebrates. Only a few studies, mostly related to human clinical cases or sero-epidemiologic evaluation of healthy animals, have reported _C. burnetii_ in South America. However, to our knowledge, _C. burnetii_ has never been reported in ticks in the continent.

During ecologic studies on _Amblyomma parvum_ and _A. tigrinum_ ticks in Cordoba Province, Argentina, engorged nymphs were collected from the common yellow toothed cavy (the rodent _Galea musteloides_) (92 _A. tigrinum_, 13 _A. parvum_). In the laboratory, engorged nymphs molted to adults, which were individually submitted to the hemolymph test with Gimenez staining for detection of rickettsiae-like organisms. By the hemolymph test, one _A. tigrinum_ female, and 2 _A. parvum_ male ticks were found to contain red-stained rickettsiae-like structures. These 3 ticks were processed individually by the shell vial technique, with the purpose of isolating intracellular bacteria in Vero cell culture. DNA from the infected cells of each of the 3 isolates was extracted and processed by PCR protocols selective for portions of 3 genes of the genus _Coxiella_. We sequenced the PCR products, finding that they were 99.9 percent (99.6 percent (556/558 nt) and 99.6 percent identical to the corresponding GenBank sequences of the North American _C. burnetii_ genes 16S rRNA, cap, and pyrG, respectively.

Ticks negative for rickettsiae-like organisms by hemolymph testing were subjected individually to DNA extraction, and 40 _A. tigrinum_ ticks yielded amplicons of the expected size for the pyrG gene. DNA sequences generated from these ticks were identical to the pyrG partial sequences obtained from the _C. burnetii_ isolates mentioned above.

Letter to the editor by:
Richard C. Pacheco, Ignacio E. Echaide, Rosiane N. Alves, Marcelo E. Beletti, Santiago Nava, and Marcelo B. Labruna

