<promed@promedmail.org>

[The initial description of Q fever as an illness was among abattoir workers in Australia. The main route of infection is the inhalation of _C. burnetii_. This desiccation-resistant obligate intracellular bacterium is shed from infected animals, usually cattle, sheep, goats or cats, especially at the time of parturition. Air samples are positive for weeks following parturition, and viable organisms are present in the soil for periods of up to 150 days.

Wild animals may be very important in the epidemiology of Q fever. Doves are thought to be responsible for introducing _C. burnetii_ to Northern Ireland. A wide variety of fish, rodents and marsupials have been shown to be infected by _C. burnetii_. Ticks are probably of great importance in maintaining the cycle of _C. burnetii_ in nature. The pathogen multiplies in the cells of the midgut of the tick and is excreted in the feces of the tick during feeding. - Mod.PMB

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: http://healthmap.org/r/1yJb.]
